{"key":"processedPost-15337913","value":{"id":15337913,"first":15336937,"last":25274114,"when":1320721737,"utime":"11/08/11 05:08 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>simon418 said:</b><br /><br />also it's not white powder/chunk it' grey granular but it turn into powder very easily in my coffee grinder<br /></blockquote><br /><br />That's an excellent way to ruin your coffee grinder for no reason.&nbsp; <br /><br />Granular gypsum is just powder gypsum with a water soluble bonding agent added.&nbsp; They make the granules because they will more easily pass through automatic spreading equipment, which is towed behind tractors on large farms.&nbsp; The powder gypsum has a tendency to jam the equipment because it packs down.&nbsp; Granular gypsum passes right through.<br /><br />Just use it in granular form and mix with your dry ingredients.&nbsp; As soon as you add water to the dry ingredients, the gypsum will dissolve back into the same form it had when first ground from solid rock.&nbsp; Don't stress over a few 'chunks' which might be left over.<br />RR","title":"Re: granular gypsum"}}